4.5 A function for portfolio metrics
Loss ratio and claim frequency are computed dozens of times in this report across different groupings. A small helper enforces a single definition and avoids subtle bugs from re-computation.


Show the code
portfolio_metrics &lt;- function(df, ...) {
  df |&gt;
    group_by(...) |&gt;
    summarise(
      policies = n(),
      exposure = sum(total_exposure, na.rm = TRUE),
      premium = sum(total_premium, na.rm = TRUE),
      incurred = sum(total_incurred, na.rm = TRUE),
      claims = sum(total_claims, na.rm = TRUE),
      .groups = "drop"
    ) |&gt;
    mutate(
      loss_ratio = incurred / premium,
      claim_freq = claims / exposure,
      avg_premium = premium / exposure,
      severity = incurred / pmax(claims, 1)
    )
}


The function returns the building blocks (policies, exposure, premium, incurred, claims) and the four ratios that follow from them. Loss ratio is aggregated as a ratio of sums rather than a mean of ratios.

5.3 Categorical variables
The portfolio descriptors get a faceted bar chart so they can be read together. Bars are ordered by inherent meaning where one exists (coverage breadth, bonus score) and by frequency otherwise. There are eight categorical descriptors.


Show the code
cat_long &lt;- ins |&gt;
  select(year, policy_type, policy_status, business_type,
         payment_frequency, bonus_score, fuel_type, circulation_area) |&gt;
  mutate(across(everything(), as.character)) |&gt;
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "variable", values_to = "level") |&gt;
  count(variable, level) |&gt;
  group_by(variable) |&gt;
  mutate(pct = n / sum(n)) |&gt;
  ungroup() |&gt;
  mutate(variable = factor(variable,
                           levels = c("year", "policy_type", "policy_status",
                                      "business_type", "payment_frequency",
                                      "bonus_score", "fuel_type",
                                      "circulation_area")))

ggplot(cat_long, aes(x = level, y = pct)) +
  geom_col(fill = "#2C5282") +
  facet_wrap(~ variable, scales = "free", ncol = 3) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = percent_format(accuracy = 1)) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "Share of policies",
       title = "Portfolio composition by descriptor") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1, size = 7))









The book is growing fast which can be seen as 2024 contributes 47 percent of all policy years, up from 19 percent in 2022, so almost half of everything in this dataset is recent. CC (third party plus two additional covers) is the dominant product at 58 percent, followed by comprehensive with excess at 26 percent. Comprehensive without excess (COMP_N) and basic third party (TP) are the smallest segments. The portfolio is heavily skewed toward annual paying customers with a good bonus history, on diesel vehicles, in inland municipalities. The 11 percent cancellation is worth keeping in mind because cancelled policies often correlate with claims related issues.

5.5 Decision point flow
The Sankey style flow connects agents to the channels they used in the leak window, weighted by the number of embargo relevant messages each pair produced. This compresses the timeline into a structural view of who pushed merger content through which channel.


Show the code
flow_data &lt;- leak_window |&gt;
  filter(embargo_hit) |&gt;
  count(agent_id, channel) |&gt;
  filter(n &gt; 0) |&gt;
  mutate(agent_id = as.character(agent_id),
         channel = as.character(channel))

nodes_df &lt;- tibble(
  name = c(agent_labels[unique(flow_data$agent_id)],
           unique(flow_data$channel)),
  type = c(rep("agent", length(unique(flow_data$agent_id))),
           rep("channel", length(unique(flow_data$channel))))
) |&gt;
  mutate(idx = row_number() - 1,
         colour = case_when(
           name %in% agent_labels ~ unname(agent_palette[
             names(agent_labels)[match(name, agent_labels)]
           ]),
           name %in% channel_levels ~ unname(channel_palette[name]),
           TRUE ~ "#CCCCCC"
         ))

agent_idx &lt;- nodes_df |&gt;
  filter(type == "agent") |&gt;
  mutate(agent_id = names(agent_labels)[match(name, agent_labels)]) |&gt;
  select(agent_id, source_idx = idx)

channel_idx &lt;- nodes_df |&gt;
  filter(type == "channel") |&gt;
  select(channel = name, target_idx = idx)

links_df &lt;- flow_data |&gt;
  left_join(agent_idx, by = "agent_id") |&gt;
  left_join(channel_idx, by = "channel")

plot_ly(
  type = "sankey",
  arrangement = "snap",
  node = list(
    label = nodes_df$name,
    color = nodes_df$colour,
    pad = 14, thickness = 18,
    line = list(color = "white", width = 0.5)
  ),
  link = list(
    source = links_df$source_idx,
    target = links_df$target_idx,
    value  = links_df$n
  )
) |&gt;
  layout(
    title = list(text = "Agent to channel flow for embargo relevant messages",
                 font = list(size = 13)),
    font = list(size = 11),
    margin = list(t = 50, b = 20)
  )












TipReading the plot



The bulk of merger relevant traffic flows through comms_huddle, which is expected because legitimate prep work happens there. The signal of concern is the weight on personal_post and anonymous_post reaching the right-hand side of the diagram. Tracing those flows back to their source identifies which agents authored the public posts that broke the embargo.
The Legal Agent contributes the largest flow to anonymous_post and a substantial share to personal_post. This is the structural fingerprint of the leak. The flow view complements the timeline by showing volume per pathway rather than per moment.








NoteThings to learn from the code chunk above



A Sankey in plotly needs three pieces of data, which are a node table with labels, a colour vector for the nodes, and a link table with numeric source and target indices that reference rows in the node table. Building the index lookups as separate tibbles and joining them in is clearer than computing indices inline, and it makes the link weights easy to inspect. The arrangement = "snap" setting prevents the user from accidentally dragging nodes into illegible positions while still allowing hover interaction. Carrying the agent and channel palettes through to the node colours keeps colour identity consistent with the rest of the report.

7.1 Defining expected behaviour
Expected behaviour for each agent role is derived from the baseline channel proportions. A message is flagged as deviant if it occurs in a channel that represents less than five percent of the agent’s baseline activity. This is a simple rule but it captures the structural anomaly of an agent using an unusual channel for them.


Show the code
baseline_props &lt;- messages_tbl |&gt;
  filter(period == "Baseline") |&gt;
  group_by(agent_id, channel) |&gt;
  summarise(baseline_n = n(), .groups = "drop_last") |&gt;
  mutate(baseline_prop = baseline_n / sum(baseline_n)) |&gt;
  ungroup() |&gt;
  complete(agent_id, channel, fill = list(baseline_n = 0, baseline_prop = 0))

messages_scored &lt;- messages_tbl |&gt;
  left_join(baseline_props, by = c("agent_id", "channel")) |&gt;
  mutate(deviant = baseline_prop &lt; 0.05)

deviant_summary &lt;- messages_scored |&gt;
  filter(deviant) |&gt;
  count(period, agent_id, channel) |&gt;
  arrange(desc(n))

deviant_summary |&gt;
  mutate(agent = agent_labels[as.character(agent_id)]) |&gt;
  select(period, agent, channel, count = n) |&gt;
  DT::datatable(rownames = FALSE,
                options = list(pageLength = 8, dom = "tip"),
                caption = "Deviant messages by agent and channel")






The table is interactive so the reader can sort and search. The largest single block of deviance is Legal Agent posting on anonymous_post, with twelve instances across the two-week window. The baseline rate for Legal on this channel is two percent, which is below the five percent threshold, which means every anonymous post by Legal is flagged.

7.4 Dimension 4: response behaviour
A message can implicitly demand a reply. The responding_to field shows whether one was given. A dumbbell chart shows each agent’s response rate in baseline versus leak window, so the magnitude of change is the line length.


Show the code
msg_lookup &lt;- messages_tbl |&gt;
  select(message_id, original_sender = agent_id, original_round = round_idx)

replies &lt;- messages_tbl |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(responding_to), responding_to != "") |&gt;
  inner_join(msg_lookup, by = c("responding_to" = "message_id"))

addressed_count &lt;- directed_msgs |&gt;
  mutate(agent_id = recipient_to_agent[recipient]) |&gt;
  filter(!is.na(agent_id)) |&gt;
  count(period, agent_id, name = "n_addressed")

reply_count &lt;- replies |&gt;
  mutate(period = as.character(period)) |&gt;
  count(period, agent_id, name = "n_replied") |&gt;
  mutate(agent_id = as.character(agent_id))

response_rates &lt;- addressed_count |&gt;
  full_join(reply_count, by = c("period", "agent_id")) |&gt;
  mutate(across(c(n_addressed, n_replied), ~ replace_na(.x, 0)),
         response_rate = if_else(n_addressed &gt; 0,
                                 n_replied / n_addressed, NA_real_)) |&gt;
  filter(agent_id %in% names(agent_labels))

response_wide &lt;- response_rates |&gt;
  select(period, agent_id, response_rate) |&gt;
  pivot_wider(names_from = period, values_from = response_rate)

if (!"Baseline" %in% names(response_wide))    response_wide$Baseline    &lt;- NA_real_
if (!"Leak window" %in% names(response_wide)) response_wide$`Leak window` &lt;- NA_real_

response_wide &lt;- response_wide |&gt;
  mutate(agent_id = factor(agent_id, levels = names(agent_labels))) |&gt;
  arrange(agent_id)

ggplot(response_wide, aes(y = fct_rev(agent_id))) +
  geom_segment(aes(x = Baseline, xend = `Leak window`, yend = fct_rev(agent_id)),
               colour = "grey60", linewidth = 0.8, na.rm = TRUE) +
  geom_point(aes(x = Baseline), colour = "#90CDF4", size = 4, na.rm = TRUE) +
  geom_point(aes(x = `Leak window`), colour = "#742A2A", size = 4, na.rm = TRUE) +
  geom_text(aes(x = Baseline, label = scales::percent(Baseline, accuracy = 1)),
            vjust = -1.2, size = 3, colour = "grey20", na.rm = TRUE) +
  geom_text(aes(x = `Leak window`, label = scales::percent(`Leak window`, accuracy = 1)),
            vjust = -1.2, size = 3, colour = "grey20", na.rm = TRUE) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = percent_format()) +
  scale_y_discrete(labels = agent_labels) +
  labs(x = "Response rate (replies given / direct messages received)",
       y = NULL,
       title = "Response rate per agent: baseline (blue) versus leak window (red)",
       subtitle = "An agent missing both dots received zero direct messages in that period") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 11) +
  theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank())















TipReading the plot



The Judge has a single baseline dot (one message received, replied to or not depending on the data) and no leak-window dot at all, because the Judge received zero direct messages in the leak window. This is the architectural failure: the compliance role had nothing to respond to.
The Legal Agent and Social Media Agent maintained high response rates in the leak window, which means they remained reachable for each other. The PR Agent’s response rate collapsed, reflecting their broader withdrawal from the conversation seen in 7.1.

7.5 Dimension 5: topical relevance
A diverging-bar chart shows the shift in topic share per agent. Bars pointing right mean the agent’s content moved toward that topic; bars pointing left mean away from it.


Show the code
topic_props &lt;- messages_tbl |&gt;
  mutate(content_lc = tolower(coalesce(content, ""))) |&gt;
  crossing(topic_patterns) |&gt;
  mutate(hit = str_detect(content_lc, pattern)) |&gt;
  group_by(period, agent_id, topic) |&gt;
  summarise(messages_on_topic = sum(hit), .groups = "drop") |&gt;
  group_by(period, agent_id) |&gt;
  mutate(total = sum(messages_on_topic),
         prop  = if_else(total &gt; 0, messages_on_topic / total, 0)) |&gt;
  ungroup()

topic_shift &lt;- topic_props |&gt;
  select(period, agent_id, topic, prop) |&gt;
  pivot_wider(names_from = period, values_from = prop, values_fill = 0) |&gt;
  mutate(shift = `Leak window` - Baseline)

ggplot(topic_shift,
       aes(x = shift, y = topic, fill = shift &gt; 0)) +
  geom_col(width = 0.6) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, colour = "grey40") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(),
                     limits = c(-0.5, 0.5)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(`TRUE` = "#742A2A", `FALSE` = "#90CDF4"),
                    guide = "none") +
  facet_wrap(~ agent_id, ncol = 4,
             labeller = labeller(agent_id = agent_labels)) +
  labs(x = "Shift in topic share (leak window minus baseline)",
       y = NULL,
       title = "Per agent: which topics increased (red) and decreased (blue) in the leak window",
       subtitle = "Each panel shows one agent's six topic shares moving from baseline to leak window") +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 10) +
  theme(panel.grid.major.y = element_blank(),
        strip.text = element_text(face = "bold"))















TipReading the plot



Every active agent shows a strong rightward Merger bar in the leak window. The Legal Agent’s leak-window mix swings sharply toward Merger and Media at the expense of Legal vocabulary. The Social Media Agent and PR Intern show similar Merger-dominated shifts. The Platform Trust Agent and PR Agent show flat bars because they produced no leak-window messages, so the shift is zero by construction. The topical anomaly is universal: every agent who spoke at all during the leak window was talking about the merger.

7.3 Agent-to-channel flow
The Sankey shows which agents pushed embargo-relevant content through which channels.


Show the code
flow_data &lt;- messages_tbl |&gt;
  filter(period == "Leak window", embargo_hit) |&gt;
  count(agent_id, channel) |&gt;
  filter(n &gt; 0) |&gt;
  mutate(agent_id = as.character(agent_id),
         channel = as.character(channel))

nodes_df &lt;- tibble(
  name = c(agent_labels[unique(flow_data$agent_id)],
           unique(flow_data$channel)),
  type = c(rep("agent", length(unique(flow_data$agent_id))),
           rep("channel", length(unique(flow_data$channel))))
) |&gt;
  mutate(
    idx = row_number() - 1,
    colour = case_when(
      name %in% agent_labels ~ unname(agent_palette[
        names(agent_labels)[match(name, agent_labels)]
      ]),
      name %in% names(channel_palette) ~ unname(channel_palette[name]),
      TRUE ~ "#CCCCCC"
    )
  )

agent_idx &lt;- nodes_df |&gt;
  filter(type == "agent") |&gt;
  mutate(agent_id = names(agent_labels)[match(name, agent_labels)]) |&gt;
  select(agent_id, source_idx = idx)

channel_idx &lt;- nodes_df |&gt;
  filter(type == "channel") |&gt;
  select(channel = name, target_idx = idx)

links_df &lt;- flow_data |&gt;
  left_join(agent_idx,   by = "agent_id") |&gt;
  left_join(channel_idx, by = "channel")

plot_ly(
  type = "sankey",
  arrangement = "snap",
  node = list(
    label = nodes_df$name, color = nodes_df$colour,
    pad = 14, thickness = 18,
    line = list(color = "white", width = 0.5)
  ),
  link = list(
    source = links_df$source_idx,
    target = links_df$target_idx,
    value  = links_df$n
  )
) |&gt;
  layout(
    title = list(text = "Agent-to-channel flow for embargo-relevant messages",
                 font = list(size = 13)),
    font = list(size = 11),
    margin = list(t = 50, b = 20)
  )












TipReading the plot



The Legal Agent is the largest contributor to anonymous_post and a substantial contributor to personal_post. The Social Media Agent contributes heavily to personal_post. Both flows reach the channels that publish to the outside world without the branded company account, which is the structural fingerprint of the breach.
